[normal]1.
[normal]4
[normal]              
[normal] The Local Government Technical Advisers Group 
[normal](
[normal]TAG
[normal])
[normal] represents a large number of local authorities in the country, these include those with highway and transport responsibilities; such as Transport for London, most London boroughs, Metropolitan authoritie
[normal]s, Unitary authorities
[normal], consultants providing highway and transport services for major local authorities and
[normal] many of the districts an
[normal]d towns in two tier authorities. 
[normal]While these ‘second tier’ authorities do not have direct responsibility for transport, 
[normal]they do have a major role in looking after significant towns and the sensible overall planning of them including providing a reasonable environment and trying to ensure
[normal],
[normal] through the Highways and Transport Authorities
[normal],
[normal] that the transport system is fit for p
[normal]urpose. 
[normal]Overall we represent over 100 different authorities.
[normal] Thus for any technical or professional group, we believe we are the most effective representative organisation likely to have a technical as well as public view on any policy issues
[normal] (we are profe
[normal]ssional advisers to the LGA)
[normal]. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]2.1
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]TAG does support and welcome the government’
[normal]s views that we need to provide good 
[normal]transport and communications
[normal] for people and the economy and we need to 
[normal]repair and renew
[normal] considerable parts of our infrastructure.  However we have grave reservations on some of the assertions included and indeed on the strategy, spending plans and possible future administrative structures.
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.2
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]We are particularly concerned that lack of clarity relating to the future of local highway authority roads will continue to increase the division between the 
[normal]2% of the network under the management of the Highways Agency and the remaining 98% managed by Loc
[normal]al Authorities 
[normal]rather than delivering the necessary integration. 
[normal]It should be noted particularly that for all 
[normal]practical purposes all journeys by whatever mode begin and end on the 98% of the road network that is managed by LAs.
[normal] It is the journeys made by t
[normal]he customer road users that are important to the economy no
[normal]t just the roads classified as T
[normal]runk roads
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.3
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]While it may be a common perception that providing additional capacity would reduce congestion and help the economy there is little evidence to this 
[normal]effect. Furthermore for big cities it can often be the case that adding to the road network can make all travel worse.
[normal] 
[normal]While this may be difficult to understand there is a wealth of published information which supports this fact. 
[normal](We have provided
[normal] some sum
[normal]mary text
[normal], references, links
[normal] and 
[normal]published 
[normal]documents that clearly 
[normal]support 
[normal]this
[normal] – please see Appendix 2
[normal])
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]3.1
[normal]              
[normal]Where communications can be achieved electronically and physical transport can be avoided
[normal],
[normal] this should be supported by Central and Local Government, individuals
[normal], 
[normal]industry and commerce - enhancing 
[normal]electronic communications, 
[normal]Broadband
[normal], 4G
[normal] etc
[normal].
[normal] is in everybody’s interests
[normal].
[normal] T
[normal]he growth in electronic communications
[normal] provides for easier 
[normal]home working 
[normal]etc
[normal].
[normal]  
[normal]and is likely to
[normal] be a 
[normal]significant and growing contributory factor in
[normal] 
[normal]the arrest of actual traffic growth
[normal],
[normal] as seen 
[normal]in the last decade
[normal].
[normal].
[normal]3.2
[normal]              
[normal]Any person or freight 
[normal]movement 
[normal]is dependent on 
[normal]the 
[normal]use of the nearly 9
[normal]8
[normal]% of the total road network that is Local Authority 
[normal]controlled
[normal] - by car, delivery vehicle,
[normal] bus, 
[normal]foot or
[normal] cycle
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]at the beginning and end of each and every journey
[normal].  Al
[normal]though it has been stated that 
[normal] 
[normal]about a third 
[normal]of vehicle miles are on the Trunk Roads it i
[normal]s really the number of overall trips that are most important.  Furthermore it is certainly desirable that all Transport and Highway authorities encourage the minimisation of the travel distance needed to meet the needs of individuals or the economy as a wh
[normal]ole
[normal] - 
[normal]packing Kent potatoes in Somerset, or driving 5 miles to an out of town supermarket for a
[normal] convenience shop
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]does not really help the economy
[normal] – policies for transport should not encourage these all too real situations
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.3
[normal]              
[normal]It is notable that Local Au
[normal]thorities have indeed managed to arrest traffic growth in many major urban areas and some smaller historic towns by effective transport and planning policies.  This has been very hard work 
[normal]and sometimes expensive 
[normal]with the con
[normal]s
[normal]traints 
[normal]of the 
[normal]1985 
[normal]Transport 
[normal]Act outside London
[normal] and
[normal] often with
[normal] less than full support by Central Government on 
[normal]issues such as 
[normal]management of parking and enforcement of moving vehicle offences
[normal].
[normal] Furthermore i
[normal]ncreased capacity particularly of 
[normal]Motorway
[normal]s
[normal] by the HA close to urban areas gener
[normal]at
[normal]es
[normal] extra car commuting traffic 
[normal]which again
[normal] contribute
[normal]s
[normal] to Local Authorities difficulties in managing their networks effectively
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.4
[normal]              
[normal]It is however welcomed that DfT circular 02/2013 
[normal](
[normal]The Strategic Road Network and the delivery of Sustainable Transport
[normal])
[normal] does suggest that trip generation should be minimised at source and sustainable modes of transport should be maximised and journey lengths minimised.  (
[normal]para 12). 
[normal] 
[normal]I
[normal]t would be highly desirable if such an objective was carried through in government planning
[normal] guidance for all developments and for the management and development of the Trunk Road network itself.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.5
[normal]              
[normal]In both the ‘Investing in Britain
[normal]’
[normal]s Future’ and 
[normal]‘
[normal]Action for Roads’ document the impression is given that a road
[normal] 
[normal]building strategy will reduce congestion in the future but it appears 
[normal]even 
[normal]from the Traffic Forecasts by the DfT that this is far from the truth
[normal] and indeed the traffic congestion is predicted to get worse even with such major expenditure on the Trunk Road 
[normal]Network. This calls into question the need for alternative strategies and spending plans 
[normal]to deliver a different outcome nationally. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.6
[normal]              
[normal]The conclusions of the Eddington review into Transport 
[normal]were that 
[normal]the major problems 
[normal]were 
[normal]in 
[normal]u
[normal]rban areas rather than 
[normal]interurban and the
[normal]re was an urgent
[normal] need for policies to reduce 
[normal]traffic
[normal] volumes.
[normal] The statement in the Forward by the Chancellor and Chief Secretary
[normal] -
[normal] “
[normal]It’s been the result of a collective national mindset that has privileged the
[normal] 
[normal]short term over the long ter
[normal]m, and has postponed difficult decisions
[normal]” could not be 
[normal]more 
[normal]true
[normal] especially
[normal] if such a roads expansion policy rather than managing our total traffic is followed
[normal].
[normal] (We should add that from the tenor of the statements made by Government that they
[normal] mistakenly
[normal] th
[normal]ink that a road enlargement policy is what is needed
[normal] rather than managing our total traffic).
[normal] 
[normal]It is 
[normal]also 
[normal]particularly notable that t
[normal]he map of the most serious congestion even on HA roads 
[normal](page 15 of Action for Roads) 
[normal]clearly shows the worst congestion clos
[normal]e to the largest urban areas.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.7
[normal]              
[normal]Funding and consequentially the management of local highway authority roads and transport services continue to remain uncertain, raising the concern of an increasing division between the strategic road network and the 
[normal]communities they purport to serve. Levels of capital funding are indicated to increase
[normal] for local highway authority roads
[normal], despite questions relating to the overall affordability, but 
[normal]certainty of funding with the corresponding benefit of establishing a pip
[normal]eline are receding, at least for the foreseeable future. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.8
[normal]              
[normal]Capital funding is increasingly being provided as 
[normal]either 
[normal]relatively small one-off grants following competition or indirectly through organisation
[normal]s
[normal] without responsibility for the network. 
[normal]Howeve
[normal]r, the greatest concern relates to revenue funding which continues to reduce; revenue reductions are directly impacting on the ability of authorities to manage transport in their areas with the consequential and inevitable outcome that congestion will incr
[normal]ease and 
[normal]ultimately 
[normal]safety decline. The revenue reductions are impacting on all aspects of transport infrastructure; bus services are being reduced, support for sustainable travel is being removed and road safety initiatives cut back. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.9
[normal]              
[normal]The fixation on
[normal] pot holes is in some respects welcome in that it is focussing attention in the deterioration of the fabric of the network but 
[normal]can 
[normal]detract from the argument relating to other essential aspects such as traffic signal maintenance, drainage 
[normal]and road markings,
[normal] all of 
[normal]which 
[normal]combine to deliver an effective, efficient and safe network. Bland statements regarding the
[normal]se
[normal] issues being the responsibility of local authorities to determine priorities within their budgets are at best unhelpful and ignore the root causes o
[normal]f the problem.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.10
[normal]              
[normal]A somewhat separate but w
[normal]orryingly 
[normal]aspect of recent cuts in government funding has been the severity of the loss of skills from the sector. This reduction is greater and m
[normal]ore sever
[normal]e
[normal] than those of the 198
[normal]0’s. The potential pipeline for major strategic road network could offer a glimmer of hope in terms of skills development and retention for the future, but only impacts on one area of the sector leaving other key areas with potentially greater uncertainty 
[normal]including transport planning, 
[normal]road safety, sustainable transport and highway maintenance. A clearer 
[normal]and more balanced 
[normal]view for the longer term investment in the
[normal] whole
[normal] local transport network is required. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]4.1
[normal]              
[normal]We welcome unreservedly the 
[normal]long overdue extra expenditure for maintenance. We would however again stress that to improve the quality of road journeys for freight
[normal],
[normal] cars
[normal],
[normal] pedestrians and cyclists
[normal],
[normal] the condition of u
[normal]rban roads and indeed rural non trunk roads need a vast improvement
[normal]. 
[normal]We
[normal] would be concerned if funding is skewed to the 
[normal]2
[normal]% of the road network rather than the 9
[normal]8
[normal]%
[normal]. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.2
[normal]              
[normal]We note on page 5 of Investing in Britain
[normal]’
[normal]s Future
[normal],
[normal] it is stated that “T
[normal]he Government has consistently prioritised capital investment over day-to-day spendi
[normal]ng
[normal]” 
[normal]and consequentially the primary benefit of the additional funding will be to 
[normal]offset
[normal] reductions in revenue budgets. 
[normal]However, this will not address the longer-term deterioration in the overall transport network, maintenance of key assets including 
[normal]traffic signals, drainage and road markings is being required to be reduced.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]5.1
[normal]              
[normal]We are concerned 
[normal]regarding
[normal] any further reduction of public and democratic control of many of our busiest interurban and urban fringe roads by making t
[normal]he Highways Agency a more arms length organisation.  The Trunk roads must be considered as part of th
[normal]e overall road 
[normal]network and indeed part of the wider Transport Network.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]5.2
[normal]              
[normal]Accountability of the HA in the new model raises concerns, it is a long held view that the HA and indeed DfT should be more directly accountable to the communities they effect by their decisions. However, there is a danger under new models whereby the HA c
[normal]ould have greater freedoms and flexibility
[normal] that 
[normal]it becomes more remote from the wider public, not 
[normal]just road users.
[normal] 
[normal]G
[normal]reater clarity
[normal] might 
[normal]only be provided in terms of financial accountability.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]5.3
[normal]              
[normal]The ability of the HA to invest outside the strategic road
[normal] network is 
[normal]welcome
[normal]d
[normal] allowing a degree of integration but is a poor substitute for the provision of adequate funding to the local authorities to address problems in their areas. Th
[normal]e framework for the HA 
[normal]must therefore include
[normal] the ability 
[normal]and encouragement 
[normal]to invest in public 
[normal]t
[normal]ransport
[normal], pedestrian and cycle  i
[normal]mprovements, 
[normal]local access provision close to HA roads, 
[normal]Smarter Travel/ Travel Planning
[normal] initiatives
[normal], Park and Ride etc
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]5.4
[normal]              
[normal]A performance specification is all very well in princip
[normal]le
[normal] but one thing we have learned is that in times of significant change
[normal],
[normal] outcomes become more difficult to predict, particularly in the longer-term. If say journey time reliability
[normal] 
[normal]is
[normal] used as a 
[normal]key 
[normal]performance measure for the Trunk Roads
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]it can be improved 
[normal]by 
[normal]diverting traffic onto 
[normal]the local highway network, providing a perverse outcome.
[normal]  
[normal]Such an outcome 
[normal]may 
[normal]be acceptable to the users of the 
[normal]2% of the 
[normal]network but would be highly unpopular with local communities who would potentially be left with no direct re
[normal]course to the HA and local authorities powerless to intervene.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]5.5
[normal]              
[normal]Regarding the identified management models each would seem to have potential drawbacks. The formal contractual model appears fraught with difficulties associated with performance increasin
[normal]g in complexity with duration of the contract.  The regulated utility model appears least appropriate given their performance and lack of alignment with broader national economic requirements
[normal];
[normal] 
[normal]for example reduced energy prices with more modest profit margi
[normal]ns would be in the public 
[normal]interest. The trust model addresses an issue of concern relating to the balance of service provision and profit but leaves the question 
[normal]of 
[normal]performance unanswered and previous statements appear to have ruled out the transfer of the
[normal] assets.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]5.6
[normal]              
[normal]Freeing the H
[normal]A from the constraints of short
[normal]–term funding and restrictive employment processes is welcomed but the
[normal]se
[normal] issues are also faced by Local 
[normal]A
[normal]uthorities 
[normal]managing
[normal] the rest of the network.  Furthermore a
[normal]t
[normal] this stage there appears to be 
[normal]no clarity regarding how funding for 
[normal]the 
[normal]new model will be resourced.  
[normal]I
[normal]t is t
[normal]o be hoped that new HA company w
[normal]ould
[normal] not run up large deficits, off book for government, as Network Rail has, as this really represents hidden public debt.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]5.7
[normal]              
[normal]T
[normal]he benefits of l
[normal]onger-term financial planning and certainty for the HA are welcomed and should secure greater commitment to workforce training in apprenticeships and also importantly higher technical skills.  However, a critical shortage of skilled staff is inevitable giv
[normal]en the rapid shrinkage we 
[normal]have suffered and without such commitments
[normal] 
[normal]will not be remedied, although given the uncertainties in the wider public sector funding, skill shortages are likely to remain in the long-term.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]How will the policies set out in the Government’s “Action for Roads” command paper improve the strategic road network for all road users, whilst also improving the environment?[bold]6.1
[normal]              
[normal]The proposals identified in Action for Roads 
[normal]c
[normal]ould
[normal] deliver greater and longer-term certainty in terms of the performance and delivery of improvements 
[normal]on 2% of 
[normal]the road network
[normal] 
[normal](
[normal]if 
[normal]delivery of (capacity) improvements are really 
[normal]required
[normal])
[normal].
[normal] However the presumption that congestion can be tackled by increased capacity and demand for growth satisfied is
[normal] not backed by evidence
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]6.2
[normal]              
[normal]There is evidence that a number of local authorities 
[normal]have been 
[normal]successfully managing congestion with growth in the
[normal]ir local economies and without the need for increases in overall road capacity. The key principle adopted being that of the integration of policy and investment programs across modes with a specific objective of sustainable growth. Greater emphasis is requ
[normal]ired regarding the coordination of investment and in particularly in terms of the working with local authorities to ensure that the economic growth is sustainable.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]6.3
[normal]              
[normal]T
[normal]he lack of clarity regarding the direction of funding for local transport raises sign
[normal]ificant concern whether sustainable growth can be achieved. Funding is being reduced both in terms of capital expenditure
[normal] (
[normal]local authority 
[normal]capital 
[normal]transport spend has reduced by almost 25% in the last two years
[normal])
[normal] and also in terms of revenue spend including
[normal] reductions in funding for maintenance and operation of public transport
[normal] (
[normal]concessionary bus fare funding for some authorities alone is facing a potential reduction of 35%
[normal])
[normal]. Government needs to “join up” its thinking regarding transport and cannot blindly a
[normal]ssume that increased investment in the Strategic Road Network alone will result in better transport outcomes.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]6.4
[normal]              
[normal]The barrier posed by the trunk road network to cyclists and walkers, particularly on the edges of urban areas is understated and the vague assumption that the movements can be accommodated on local networks an overstated simplification. In many instances k
[normal]ey links between communities have been severed and significant investment is required if these barriers to efficient and sustainable movement are to be removed. A clearer commitment to supporting such improvements to provide key links which may well be on 
[normal]local networks, is required. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]6.5
[normal]              
[normal]Investment in new technology and support for alternative fuels is welcome, however without better integration of policy and investment across modes and networks there is a danger that 
[normal]even 
[normal]the environmental cost
[normal],
[normal] of 
[normal]tryin
[normal]g to 
[normal]achiev
[normal]e
[normal] growth
[normal] by trunk road enlargement
[normal] will be significant.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]How does the Government’s policy for roads link with planning for other transport modes?[bold]6.6
[normal]              
[normal]In part this is covered in the response
[normal] and section 3
[normal] above and there is great concern that the outcomes may not be desirable particularly in terms of both commuter and longer distance journeys. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]6.7
[normal]              
[normal]One potential outcome, is that additional capacity provided in the strategic road network will result in the
[normal] transfer of trips from public transport
[normal] and longer journeys for goods and people
[normal]. If this is to be avoided coordination in terms of policy development and delivery need to be integrated.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]How reliable is the Government’s forecast for growth in demand for [bold]the strategic road network? How should the Government deal with uncertainty in its forecast?[bold]&#xa0;[bold]6.8
[normal]              
[normal]Forecasts provide potential indications of outcomes; the fundamental assumption that high growth in the economy must result in higher levels of traffic needs 
[normal]to be challenged and highest traffic levels should be considered a failure of transport policy rather than successful economic policy.
[normal] It is notable that even in London the DfT is predicting traffic increases however 
[normal]London has grown substantially in popul
[normal]ation terms and economic performance over the last 20 years without 
[normal]road 
[normal]traffic increases.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]How can we improve the reliability and efficiency of travel on the strategic road network? What impact will new technology have?[bold]6.9
[normal]              
[normal]Reducing the total amount of (
[normal]particularly car) traffic on the network by  p
[normal]romoting public transport and other more sustainable modes of transport
[normal], support local planning authorities to ensure that all new development is located and designed for sustainable transport, provide 
[normal]better a
[normal]nd timely information to enable users to make choices regarding modes and times of journeys.
[normal] Support companies and individuals in sustainable travel options.  Invest in electronic communications to avoid the need for some travel.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]6.10
[normal]              
[normal]While the
[normal]re
[normal] 
[normal]may be s
[normal]cope in the future to increase the capacity of the 
[normal]strategic road
[normal] network by electronic measures 
[normal]these will not be available in the 
[normal]foreseeable
[normal] future for most of the 98% of the network
[normal] so unlikely to be effective for improvement of reliability of journeys 
[normal]e
[normal]ven if such measures did not increase traffic levels.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]6.11
[normal]              
[normal]Variable speed limits more electronic enforcement and better identification and more reliable information to drivers and t
[normal]raffic control managers could help reduce incidents and accidents causing congestion.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]What mechanisms are there for Government to increase investment in strategic roads and attract new investors? Are there good examples from other countries that could be [bold]applied in the UK? [bold]6.12
[normal]              
[normal]We have previously given verbal evidence in answer to a question by the Committee that we considered that generally there was an adequate strategic road network in the country nevertheless its management, integration with national 
[normal]and local transport strategies and maintenance could be improved.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]6.13
[normal]              
[normal]To attract investment there must be a revenue stream available. TAG are on record as supporting congestion charging/ road user charging as is done in many countries throughout the worl
[normal]d
[normal] to fund maintenance of the strategic road network.  We do not believe that such charging should be for isolated links but managed as part of an overall transport strategy.  We also recognise the political difficulties in the introduction of charging regi
[normal]mes, nevertheless they are generally supported by industry to reduce congestion and help the economy.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]How should the Highways Agency be reformed to make it “the world’s leading highway operator”? What roles should Government and the private sector play to[bold] ensure better management of the strategic road network?[bold]6.14
[normal]              
[normal]The first step in improving the Highways Agency is to ensure
[normal] that it does not exist in isolation and needs to be based on a sound integrated transport policy and treat as a whole network involvi
[normal]ng LAs
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]We hope that this evidence will be useful to the Committee. We would be pleased to elaborate, provide any supporting evidence by additional documentation and verbally in front of the Committee.
[normal]&#xa0;
