[normal]Appendix 2 to TAG evidence to HOCTC Strategic Roads Inquiry[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Summary, links[bold] and published reports on road building induced traffic and congestion[bold]There is
[normal] very strong 
[normal]evidence 
[normal](but not as widely known as it should be) 
[normal]that road building can increase traffic levels enormously; although the mechanisms – mode change, redistribution,
[normal] peak narrowing, genuine new trips etc 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]resulting in the extra traffic is less clear.
[normal]Congestion at the end of the new roads and elsewhere from the extra traffic
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]although very visible, 
[normal]is much harder to quantify properly.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] 
[normal]The December 1994 
[normal]SACTRA
[normal] report
[normal] 
[normal] ‘Trunk Roads and the Generation of Traffic’ 
[normal]is probably the most robust evidence and analysis of all this.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] 
[normal]The SACTRA work itself pulled on a number of different evidence sources - not only the before-and-after traffic counts but also inferences from la
[normal]rge numbers of studies of values of time, demand elasticities, differential growth rates, and surveys. It was because all these told a broadly consistent story that SACTRA felt able to be more decisive in its conclusions than the DTp was expecting at the t
[normal]ime. 
[normal]Since then there has been one completely different type of evidence base as well: this is the complementary literature on traffic reduction following road space reductions (pedestrianisation, bus lanes, disasters, maintenance closures, etc). This is
[normal] important in its own right, but also significant in giving confidence that the induced traffic effect is not an artefact due to economic growth or similar. The largest empirical compilation is a book Cairns S, Hass-Klau C and Goodwin P (1998) Traffic Effe
[normal]ct of Highway Capacity Reductions, Landor Publishing, London, with some updating papers subsequently of which one was awarded a gold medal by the Institution of Civil Engineers.
[normal]SACTRA does show that the net effect of road enlargements could actually creat
[normal]e more congestion.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] Mogridge and Thompson really propounded this 
[normal]in their various books and papers 
[normal]and it certainly can apply most in big cities on radial routes. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Explained simply there is a vic
[normal]i
[normal]ous circle --- more road space – more car use - 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]less public
[normal] transport use – fares go up, frequency goes down – more people transfer to cars etc and the new equilibrium point is a lower level of service in both cars and Public Transport.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Apart from SACTRA there is:
[normal]It is interesting to note
[normal] that 
[normal]SACTRA came out during a 
[normal]Conservative 
[normal]Government and Transport 
[normal]M
[normal]inister Stephen Norris said at the time that the government would not have built so many roads if they had known about it.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]While this gives robust evidence of roads generating traffic t
[normal]here is also substantial evidence that extra roadspace and higher speeds do not necessarily provide economic benefits. 
[normal]Reference can also be made to the 1998 SACTRA report on roads and economic regeneration which included doubts that the economic benefits could be as high as the calculated time savings. We also know that the 
[normal]‘economic benefits’ 
[normal]calculated 
[normal]largely on basis 
[normal]of predicted 
[normal]time savings are
[normal] highly artificial
[normal].
[normal]It appears that 
[normal]the statements of certain business people and the roads lobby
[normal] is being used to make the case for Trunk road improvements rather than any evidence.  I
[normal]t is an easy message to say that widening 
[normal]a road would appear to be a solution to congestion! The real message on transport policy is much more complicated.
[normal]Phil Goodwin’s article in LTT[bold]Induced traffic again. And again. And again.[bold]Phil Goodwin[bold]When the costs of travel are reduced, people do more 
[normal]of it. When the costs of car travel are reduced, people use cars more. Why are these obvious propositions so forgettable that they need to be proved anew every decade?
[normal]It was way back in 1925 that the opening of a new section on the Great West Road demonst
[normal]rated 'the remarkable manner in which new roads generate new traffic', as Bressey wrote in 1937.  Soon forgotten. Glanville and Smeed at the Road Research Laboratory rediscovered it in 1958, and Foster, at Oxford, in 1963, and it was remembered long enough
[normal] to appear in Ministry of Transport advice in 1968, which said:
[normal]"Generated traffic on large schemes has often amounted to between 5% and 25% over and above the normal forecast traffic level…larger in exceptional cases"
[normal]Within three years the advice disappeared (nobody ever said why), and generated traffic was routinely not calculated for road schemes. The DoT took a legal case to the House of Lords to prevent such forecasts being challenged by objectors. But the evidence
[normal] kept re-appearing: a GLC study demonstrated it empirically in 1985, as did Martin Mogridge and his colleagues in 1987, and it was sharply reinforced in 1988 after the M25 exceeded its long term forecast traffic growth within months of opening. 
[normal]In 1994 SA
[normal]CTRA, the Standing Advisory Committee on Trunk Road Assessment, published its best known report, on what it renamed 'induced' traffic. The average traffic flow on 151 improved roads was 10.4% higher than forecasts which omitted induced traffic, and  16.4% 
[normal]higher than forecast on 85 alternative routes that improvements had been intended to relieve. In a dozen more detailed case studies the measured increase in traffic ranged from 9% to 44% in the short run, and 20% to 178% in the longer run.  This fitted in 
[normal]with other evidence on elasticities, and aggregate data. The conclusion was 
[normal]"an average road improvement, for which traffic growth due to all other factors is forecast correctly, will see an additional [ie induced] 10% of base traffic in the short term an
[normal]d 20% in the long term"
[normal]The Department of Transport accepted this. The report was updated it in a special issue of 'Transportation' in 1996 (including my own review, as lead author of the 'evidence' chapters 
[normal]of the SACTRA report).  Bob Noland and others fo
[normal]r the USA, and many authors in Europe, have since demonstrated similar international results.
[normal]Fast forward to July this year. CPRE published a report by Lilli Matson, Lynn Sloman, Ian Taylor, and John Elliott. The authors were known to me - I worked with L
[normal]illi on the Ten Year Plan for Transport, with a report we called 'Running to Stand Still'; with Lynn on 'Smarter Choices', and also the West Midlands TIF programme; and with John (who did the original 1985 GLC study, with Jill Beardwood and Steve Purnell) 
[normal]on the Thames Gateway Bridge.  They are a serious group of engaged professionals, and I opened their report with interest.
[normal]It's called 'Beyond Transport Infrastructure', and what they have done is look in detail at three big schemes on the A27, A34 and M65
[normal], and a further ten schemes on the A5, A6, A41, A43, A46, A66, A500 and A1033. These were schemes undertaken 
[normal]after[bold] SACTRA's 1994 report had been finished and accepted. They reported:
[normal]"Careful scrutiny of the traffic flow data suggests that traffic growth a
[normal]fter the scheme opened has been significantly higher than growth on other nearby road corridors or national traffic growth"
[normal]"…in all three case studies the current traffic flows are near or already in excess of what was predicted for 2010. In towns with by
[normal]passes, such as Newbury and Polegate, the new roads did significantly reduce the town centre traffic levels. However, these reductions are not as great as originally forecast and there has subsequently been regrowth in traffic levels on the bypassed roads.
[normal] The net effect in combination with the new road is generally a considerable overall increase in traffic".
[normal]Their final conclusion is remarkably restrained. After noting the Highways Agency's own explanations for the extra traffic growth, (which were intrig
[normal]uingly similar to those rejected by SACTRA 12 years earlier), they write 
[normal]"Nevertheless, in view of the fact that many of the schemes reviewed have demonstrated significant increases in traffic volumes (in the range of 10-35%, within a period of one to two
[normal] years after opening), there would seem a strong case to consider the issue of induced traffic in more detail in future evaluations".
[normal]So 1925, 1937, 1958, 1963, 1968, 1985, 1987, 1988, 1994, 1996, now 2006: for eighty years, every eight years on average th
[normal]ere has been the same experience, the same conclusions - even, for goodness sake, more or less the same figures. The evidence has been consistent,  recurrent, unchallenged by serious countervailing evidence, but repeatedly forgotten. CPRE have done us a se
[normal]rvice, I think, but really it should just not have been possible for them to find, 12 years after SACTRA, the same mistakes.
[normal]There may well be situations when it is justified to encourage more traffic, but this should be done cautiously, with eyes wide ope
[normal]n about the implications, not by denial. Induced traffic tends to increase environmental damage, and usually tends to reduce the calculated benefit-cost ratio of a road improvement, because the period of relief from congestion will be shorter than planned;
[normal] also because the benefit to the marginal extra travellers is less; and because assuming the extra traffic is not induced artificially makes the 'without' case worse than it really would be. It is a bit more complicated to predict.
[normal]Maybe that's the problem
[normal]. The methods you can use if there is no induced traffic are cheaper, and have the incidental side effect of uplifting the calculated benefit. If the promoter of a scheme is the same agency as is responsible for its appraisal, that's two quite big incentiv
[normal]es to get it wrong, and no countervailing pressure to get it right. Except, perhaps, the embarrassment of the next research study? But that will be nearly a decade later, and somebody else's problem. 
